<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-12-06T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-12-06T11:00:00-05:00" n="196" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d196">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">838.00/2620a: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the High Commissioner in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Russell</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-12-06T11:00:00-05:00">December 6, 1929—11
                                a.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>63. While temporary detention of persons fomenting disorder may of course
                            prove necessary the Department would not approve the trial of Haitians
                            for serious offenses by military courts or the imposition of heavy
                            sentences except in extreme cases and after the Department had had an
                            opportunity to consider the facts and approve in advance the institution
                            of proceedings.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
